04828nam a22007335i 9780674986022DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749860227 a10.4159/97806749860222doi  a(DE-B1597)500397  a(OCoLC)1028732101  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a363.728 8223  aLC 28385qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90637:8941 aDoron, Assa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWaste of a Nation :bGarbage and Growth in India /cRobin Jeffrey, Assa Doron. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b20 halftones, 4 maps, 4 charts, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Maps, Illustrations, and Tables -- tPreface -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction -- t1. Time and Place -- t2. Growth and Garbage -- t3. Sewage and Society -- t4. Recycling and Value -- t5. Technology and Imperfection -- t6. Local Governments and Limitations -- t7. Occupations and Possibilities -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn India, you can still find the kabaadiwala, the rag-and-bone man. He wanders from house to house buying old newspapers, broken utensils, plastic bottles—anything for which he can get a little cash. This custom persists and recreates itself alongside the new economies and ecologies of consumer capitalism. Waste of a Nation offers an anthropological and historical account of India’s complex relationship with garbage. Countries around the world struggle to achieve sustainable futures. Assa Doron and Robin Jeffrey argue that in India the removal of waste and efforts to reuse it also lay waste to the lives of human beings. At the bottom of the pyramid, people who work with waste are injured and stigmatized as they deal with sewage, toxic chemicals, and rotting garbage. Terrifying events, such as atmospheric pollution and childhood stunting, that touch even the wealthy and powerful may lead to substantial changes in practices and attitudes toward sanitation. And innovative technology along with more effective local government may bring about limited improvements. But if a clean new India is to emerge as a model for other parts of the world, a “binding morality” that reaches beyond the current environmental crisis will be required. Empathy for marginalized underclasses—Dalits, poor Muslims, landless migrants—who live, almost invisibly, amid waste produced predominantly for the comfort of the better-off will be the critical element in India’s relationship with waste. Solutions will arise at the intersection of the traditional and the cutting edge, policy and practice, science and spirituality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCastezIndia. 0aRefuse and refuse disposalzIndia. 0aRefuse and refuse disposal-India. 0aSalvage (Waste, etc.)zIndia. 0aSalvage (Waste, etc.)-India. 0aSewage disposalzIndia. 0aSewage disposal-India. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aJeffrey, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674986022?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674986022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674986022/original  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_